'''James Joseph Corbett''' (November 10, 1919 &ndash; January 29, 1967) was an American sports administrator who served as [[athletics director]] at [[LSU Tigers|Louisiana State University]] from 1954 until his death in 1967.
==Biography==
Corbett was born in [[Woburn, Massachusetts]] and attended high school in nearby [[Arlington, Massachusetts|Arlington]]. He graduated from [[Southeastern Louisiana College]] in 1944.<ref name="obit"/>
In addition to his role at LSU, Corbett also served as the first president of the [[National Association of Collegiate Directors of Athletics]] from 1965–1966,<ref name="obit">{{cite news |title=LSU Athletic Head Jim Corbett Dead |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/213903957/?terms=Jim%2BCorbett |work=[[The Times (Shreveport)|The Shreveport Times]]|accessdate=August 2, 2018 |date=January 30, 1967 |location=Shreveport, Louisiana |page=1|subscription=yes}}</ref> and for more than 10 years was a member of the [[Sugar Bowl]] Executive Committee.<ref name="award">{{cite news |title=Sugar Bowl Gives Award for Corbett |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/212966254/?terms=Corbett%2BAward |accessdate=August 2, 2018 |work=[[The Times (Shreveport)|The Shreveport Times]] |date=April 18, 1967 |location=Shreveport, Louisiana |page=19|subscription=yes}}</ref>
He died of a massive heart attack in [[New Orleans]], aged only 47. LSU President John A. Hunter said, "Not only is it a tragedy as far as LSU is concerned, but it is a tragic personal loss because we all loved him so much. I think he ran one of the most efficient athletic departments in the United States and we never had an employee more dedicated to LSU than Jim was."<ref name="obit"/>
==Legacy== The National Association of Collegiate Directors of Athletics (NACDA) established the [[Corbett Award]], which is presented annually "to the collegiate administrator who through the years has most typified Corbett's devotion to intercollegiate athletics and worked unceasingly for its betterment." The first recipient was [[Bernie Moore]], commissioner emeritus for the [[Southeastern Conference]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Athletic Directors Meet in Minneapolis |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/82200040/?terms=Corbett%2BAward |accessdate=August 2, 2018 |work=The La Crosse Tribune |date=June 15, 1967 |location=La Crosse, Wisconsin |page=16|subscription=yes}}</ref>
Three months after Corbett's death, the Sugar Bowl Executive Committee established a memorial award in his name. It honored the most outstanding male or female collegiate athlete of the year in Louisiana, as selected by a panel of Louisiana's sports journalists.<ref name="award"/>
