{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}} {{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}} {{Infobox person | name = John Crabbe Cunningham | image = | caption = | birth_date = 1927 | death_date = 31 January {{Death year and age|1980|1927}} | birth_place = [[Scotland]] | death_place = [[Anglesey]], [[Holyhead]] | death_cause = Drowning | spouse = Married | parents = | children = | signature = }}
'''John Crabbe Cunningham''' (1927 – 31 January 1980) was a Scottish climber. Born in [[Glasgow]], he climbed extensively in the [[Mountains and hills of Scotland|Scottish mountains]], where he pioneered new techniques of [[ice climbing]].<ref name="docs.google.com">{{cite journal |url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:ZwQJdtiWXUgJ:www.alpinejournal.org.uk/Contents/Contents_1972_files/AJ%25201972%252075-79%2520Cunningham%2520Ice.pdf+john+cunningham+climber&hl=en&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESghxrl4jl3DBFXjMCV1Ts6VE5kkOmH3lUOo828FjO8Ib4G1g251P84vcf08_4zVNMM37nRKOf2Lr2c6l9omYKV4YMejEWIQh6alFxjuZgLVIu8OkpdMy6JQETocRK8JSbpy49lw&sig=AHIEtbTiDUeEfMM4G1Y-0rWawokdfbJHPw&pli=1 |title=New ice climbing techniques and equipment |first1=John |last1=Cunningham |first2=Bill |last2=March |journal=[[Alpine Journal]] |pages=75–79}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/scotland/greatclimb/sec4_pg6.shtml |title=Old Climbers & Bold Climbers: A brief history of northern Cairngorm climbing |publisher=BBC |accessdate=13 September 2011}}</ref>
For several years, he worked for the [[British Antarctic Survey]] (BAS) of the [[British Antarctic Territory]] (BAT). On 23 November 1964, he became the first to climb [[Antarctica]]'s [[Mount Jackson (Antarctica)|Mount Jackson]].<ref name=Cunningham>{{Cite web|url=http://www.alpinejournal.org.uk/Contents/Contents_1988-89_files/AJ%201988%20184-190%20Hattersley-Smith%20Antarctic.pdf|format=pdf|title= Mountaineers and Skiers in British Antarctic Territory Place-names|accessdate=27 December 2012|publisher=Alpine Journal Org|quote=Of the many young mountaineers that have served at the BAS stations over the years, space allows mention of only two. J. C. Cunningham (1927–80)...on 23 November 1964 he led the first ascent of Mount Jackson, Palmer Land (3180m); the highest peak in the BAT}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.philwickens.co.uk/download/files/ARTICLE_ClimbMagazine_Sept2011.pdf|format=pdf|title=Exploring the Frozen World|publisher=Mountain World, Climb Magazine.com|quote=ascent... [of] the highest mountain in the entire Peninsula, Mt Jackson at {{Convert|3188|m}} well to the south in remote Palmer Land, fell to the notorious Scot, John Cunningham, in 1964}}</ref> In 1960–61, he was a member of the Falkland Islands Dependencies Survey,<ref name="Headland1989">{{cite book|author=R K Headland|title=Chronological List of Antarctic Expeditions and Related Historical Events. [Mit Abb.] (1. Publ.) – Cambridge [usw.]: Cambridge Univ. Press (1989). 730 S. 8°|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Sg49AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA413|accessdate=27 December 2012|year=1989|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-30903-5|pages=395, 413–}}</ref> serving as Station Commander at Stonington Island in 1962–63. He was a member of the British Antarctic Survey, and was Station Commander of [[Adelaide Island]] in 1964–65. He was also a member of the South Georgia Survey of 1955–56. He died after a climbing accident off "sea-cliffs" of mountains of [[Holyhead]] on 31 January 1980, when was carried away by sea waves to his death as he did not know how to swim.<ref name="Hattersley-Smith1988">{{cite journal|last=Hattersley-Smith|first=G. |year=1988|title=Mountaineers and Skiers in British Antarctic Territory Place-names|journal=The Alpine Journal|pages=190|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:c1cq-mcVpgMJ:www.alpinejournal.org.uk/Contents/Contents_1988-89_files/AJ%25201988%2520184-190%2520Hattersley-Smith%2520Antarctic.pdf+&hl=en&gl=us&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESiz9R-4r286SoLUgAc8APN9g-_YtkX2TLYGoX0qeMaxq6MLuBLmPmnwSKykIf4sRwO7O714wxP-bMtBqo2OxyP8jMMwLqknR6COPJBo1wbPa7Yq8coqLvQiMS5OuY1R12LO4Y0X&sig=AHIEtbTHapHHb4jKxTozbx_zrtzmSnmfyw}}</ref><ref name=Hard>{{Cite web|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/hard-man-of-the-hills-1.272714|title=Hard Man of the Hills|accessdate=28 December 2012|publisher= Herald Scotland: The Herald}}</ref>
==Professional years== During the 1950s and '60s, Cunningham went to [[New Zealand]], [[India]] and [[Antarctica]]. He wanted to climb to [[Mt. Everest]], and in 1953 he had gone to [[Nepal]] via India with Dr. [[Hamish MacInnes]], also a Scottish mountaineer, to start his climb. However, [[Edmund Hillary|Hillary]] and [[Tenzing Norgay|Tenzing]] had made it to the top of Mount Everest before he could begin.<ref name=Hard/>
He then started his career with the British Antarctic Survey. He was the base leader at Adelaide Island. In the 1970s, after he returned to Scotland, he became an instructor at the Glenmore Lodge near Aviemore. In this capacity he perfected innovations in techniques for front point [[Crampons|cramponing]] and use of [[Ice axe|curved pick ice axes]] on steep sloping ice.<ref name=Hard/> He had used this front point technique while working in Antarctica on icebergs and cliffs with a slope of 70 to 90 degrees.<ref name="docs.google.com"/> In 1976 he became an instructor at [[I M Marsh Campus]] in Liverpool.<ref name=Hard/> In 1980, he took his students for practical instruction on climbing to the [[South Stack]] cliffs on [[Anglesey]]. Here he drowned on 31 January 1980 after being swept into the sea, as he did not know how to swim. His students survived.<ref name=Hard/>
==Honors== Cunningham is the namesake of [[Mount Cunningham]] ({{Convert|1220|m}}) in the [[Queen Maud Bay]] at the southern end of [[South Georgia Island|South Georgia]],<ref name="Hattersley-Smith1988"/><ref name=Hard/> His biography, titled ''Creagh Dhu Climber, the life and times of John Cunningham'', was published by Ernest Press.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Connor |first=John |year=1999 |title=Creagh Dhu Climber, the life and times of John Cunningham |publisher=Ernest Press |isbn=978-0-948153-54-9}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mountainsmounts.com/mountain/50233/mount-cunningham/ |title=Mount Cunningham |work=Mountains mounts |accessdate=13 September 2011}}</ref>
