{{use British English|date=April 2016}} {{use dmy dates|date=April 2016}} '''William St Julien Arabin''' (1773{{snd}}15 December 1841) was a [[United Kingdom|British]] lawyer and judge who served as the [[Judge Advocate General (United Kingdom)|Judge-Advocate-General of the Army]] for a three-and-a-half-month period (6 November 1838{{snd}}21 February 1839).
Arabin was born either in [[Norwich]] or abroad, the only surviving son of General William John Arabin of Ireland, who left him significant estates in Essex and Middlesex.<ref name="times">{{cite news |title=Death of Mr. Serjeant Arabin |work=[[The Times]] |publisher=The Times Digital Archive |page=4 |date=17 December 1841 }}</ref><ref name="gent">{{cite journal|title=Mr. Serjeant Arabin|journal=The Gentleman's Magazine|date=1842|page=219}}</ref> He was descended from one of the oldest families in [[Provence]]. His Huguenot ancestor Bartholomew d'Arabin fled to Holland after the [[revocation of the edict of Nantes]] in 1685, and came over to England with King [[William III of England|William III]] in 1688.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Marshall|first1=John|title=Royal Naval Biography|date=1831|publisher=Longman, Hurst, Rees, Orme, and Brown|page=69|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z11HAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA69|accessdate=16 July 2017|language=en}}</ref> Arabin attended [[St Paul's School, London]] and [[Corpus Christi College, Cambridge]]. He was admitted to [[Inner Temple]] in 1793, and was [[called to the bar]] in 1801. He was appointed [[serjeant-at-law]] in 1824.<ref>''Cambridge University Alumni: 1261-1900''</ref>
He was Deputy [[Recorder of London|Recorder of the City of London]]. He served as Judge-Advocate-General of the Army 1838{{ndash}}39. He was a judge of the [[Central Criminal Court]] and of Sheriffs' Court, London. He was a [[Verderer]] of the forests of [[Epping Forest|Epping]] and [[Hainault Forest|Hainault]].<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=WPPcP39XDDIC&pg=PA65&lpg=PA65&dq=William+St+Julien+Arabin&source=bl&ots=ULhBqosFAK&sig=5UpSjqYDWHi7JdRK4PW6Kkino1A&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwid6tzI06zMAhVKLZoKHWSDBfwQ6AEIVTAM#v=onepage&q=William%20St%20Julien%20Arabin&f=false |title=Alumni Cantabrigienses |editor-first1=John |editor-last1=Venn |editor-first2=John Archibald |editor-last2=Venn |page=65 |date=September 2011 |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |isbn=9781108036115 |accessdate=26 April 2016}}</ref>
As a judge, Arabin was known as an eccentric figure who was notorious for his confused pronouncements. Some of his most famous quotes include: * ''If there ever was a case of clearer evidence than this of persons acting together, this case is that case...'' and * ''They will steal the very teeth out of your mouth as you walk through the streets &mdash; I know it from experience...''
Arabin married Mary Meux in Camden in 1802.<ref>''London, England, Church of England Marriages and Banns, 1754-1921''</ref> He died at Arabin House in High Beech, [[Waltham Abbey (town)|Waltham Abbey]], Essex, in 1841.<ref name="gent"/>
